Feature: Document Submission State Machine
  As a document processing system
  I want to manage submission lifecycles through a defined state machine
  So that documents follow a controlled review and approval process

  Background:
    Given the submission store is empty
    And the application is running

  # ━━ GROUP A: Key Examples (6 scenarios) ━━

  # Why: Core creation — new submissions start in draft state
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: Creating a submission starts in draft state
    When I create a submission for client "CLT-000001" with document type "standard"
    Then the request should succeed with a created status
    And the submission state should be "draft"
    And the submission history should contain 0 transitions

  # Why: Core happy path — full lifecycle from draft to approved
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: A submission progresses from draft through to approval
    Given a submission in "draft" state exists
    When I submit the submission with submitted_by "alice"
    Then the submission state should be "submitted"
    When I assign the submission for review with assigned_to "bob"
    Then the submission state should be "under_review"
    When I approve the submission with decision notes "All documentation verified and complete"
    Then the submission state should be "approved"
    And the submission history should contain 3 transitions

  # Why: Rejection path — alternative terminal state
  @key-example @smoke
  Scenario: A submission under review can be rejected
    Given a submission in "under_review" state exists
    When I reject the submission with reason "Missing required supporting documents" and code "INCOMPLETE"
    Then the submission state should be "rejected"

  # Why: Recall — returning to draft from submitted
  @key-example
  Scenario: A submitted submission can be recalled to draft
    Given a submission in "submitted" state exists
    When I recall the submission to draft
    Then the submission state should be "draft"
    And all assignment fields should be cleared

  # Why: Recall from under_review — also allowed
  @key-example
  Scenario: A submission under review can be recalled to draft
    Given a submission in "under_review" state exists
    When I recall the submission to draft
    Then the submission state should be "draft"

  # Why: API retrieval includes full history
  @key-example
  Scenario: Retrieving a submission shows the full transition history
    Given a submission that has been submitted and assigned for review
    When I retrieve the submission by ID
    Then the response should contain the submission's full transition history
    And each history entry should contain the from state, to state, action, actor, and timestamp

  # ━━ GROUP B: Boundary Conditions (4 scenarios) ━━

  # Why: Decision notes minimum length — just at boundary (10 chars)
  @boundary
  Scenario: Approval with exactly 10 characters of notes succeeds
    Given a submission in "under_review" state exists
    When I approve the submission with decision notes "1234567890"
    Then the submission state should be "approved"

  # Why: Decision notes below minimum — just outside boundary (9 chars)
  @boundary @negative
  Scenario: Approval with fewer than 10 characters of notes fails
    Given a submission in "under_review" state exists
    When I attempt to approve the submission with decision notes "123456789"
    Then the transition should fail
    And the error should indicate insufficient decision notes

  # Why: Rejection reason minimum length — just at boundary (10 chars)
  @boundary
  Scenario: Rejection with exactly 10 characters of reason succeeds
    Given a submission in "under_review" state exists
    When I reject the submission with reason "1234567890" and a valid rejection code
    Then the submission state should be "rejected"

  # Why: Rejection reason below minimum — just outside boundary
  @boundary @negative
  Scenario: Rejection with fewer than 10 characters of reason fails
    Given a submission in "under_review" state exists
    When I attempt to reject the submission with reason "123456789"
    Then the transition should fail

  # ━━ GROUP C: Negative Cases (6 scenarios) ━━

  # Why: Invalid transition — cannot go from draft to approved directly
  @negative
  Scenario: Direct transition from draft to approved is rejected
    Given a submission in "draft" state exists
    When I attempt to approve the submission
    Then the transition should fail
    And the submission state should still be "draft"

  # Why: Invalid transition — cannot go from approved to anything
  @negative
  Scenario: No transitions are allowed from approved state
    Given a submission in "approved" state exists
    When I attempt to submit the submission
    Then the transition should fail
    And the submission state should still be "approved"

  # Why: Invalid transition — cannot go from rejected to anything
  @negative
  Scenario: No transitions are allowed from rejected state
    Given a submission in "rejected" state exists
    When I attempt to recall the submission to draft
    Then the transition should fail
    And the submission state should still be "rejected"

  # Why: Submit requires submitted_by — cannot be empty
  @negative
  Scenario: Submitting without a submitted_by value fails
    Given a submission in "draft" state exists
    When I attempt to submit the submission with an empty submitted_by
    Then the transition should fail

  # [ASSUMPTION: confidence=low] Rejection codes controlled set is INCOMPLETE, INVALID, DUPLICATE, OUT_OF_SCOPE
  # Why: Rejection requires a code from the controlled set
  @negative
  Scenario: Rejection with an invalid rejection code fails
    Given a submission in "under_review" state exists
    When I attempt to reject with an invalid rejection code "MADE_UP_CODE"
    Then the transition should fail

  # Why: API returns 409 for invalid transitions, not 400
  @negative
  Scenario: Invalid transition via API returns conflict status
    Given a submission in "draft" state exists
    When I request a transition to "approved" via the API
    Then the response should indicate a conflict

  # ━━ GROUP D: Edge Cases (6 scenarios) ━━

  # Why: History is ordered chronologically
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Transition history is recorded in chronological order
    Given a submission that has progressed from draft to approved
    Then the history entries should be in chronological order
    And the first entry should show draft to submitted
    And the last entry should show under_review to approved

  # Why: Paginated list with filters
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Submissions can be listed filtered by state and client ID
    Given submissions exist for multiple clients in various states
    When I list submissions filtered by state "draft" and client "CLT-000001"
    Then only submissions matching both filters should be returned
    And the response should contain pagination metadata

  # Why: Recall clears assignment fields
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Recall from under_review clears assigned_to and submitted_by
    Given a submission in "under_review" state assigned to "bob" and submitted by "alice"
    When I recall the submission to draft
    Then the submission state should be "draft"
    And the assigned_to field should be cleared
    And the submitted_by field should be cleared

  # Why: Security — injection in actor/notes fields
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Transition with injection characters in actor and notes is handled safely
    Given a submission in "under_review" state exists
    When I approve the submission with decision notes "'; DROP TABLE submissions; --" by actor "<script>alert(1)</script>"
    Then the submission state should be "approved"
    And the stored notes should be exactly "'; DROP TABLE submissions; --"
    And the stored actor should be exactly "<script>alert(1)</script>"

  # Why: Concurrency — simultaneous transitions on the same submission
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Simultaneous transitions on the same submission do not corrupt state
    Given a submission in "under_review" state exists
    When I simultaneously attempt to approve and reject the submission
    Then exactly one transition should succeed
    And the submission should be in either "approved" or "rejected" state
    And the history should reflect only the successful transition

  # Why: Data integrity — failed transition leaves state unchanged
  @edge-case
  Scenario: Failed transition leaves submission state completely unchanged
    Given a submission in "draft" state exists
    When I attempt an invalid transition to "approved"
    Then the submission state should still be "draft"
    And the submission history should contain 0 transitions
    And the updated_at timestamp should not have changed
